title: For Sale:  Pre 70 Series Colt Customized by Pachmary
postcontent: This pistol is very unique. It is a pre-70 series Colt. This pistol was made in 1964, according to the serial number. The finish is in Colt's Royal Blue and retains over 95% of the original finish. If you will look closely, you will see a pin in the frame above the trigger, it has a bearing trigger, you can see the steel bearing directly behind the trigger,instead of the typical trigger bar, this pistol has "Pachmayr" "Los Angeles" stamped under the slide, you can tell the slide/frame have been fitted, it has micro adjustable sights, the barrel, slide and other parts have the last 2 digits of the serial number stamped on them, this was done to make sure the gun was re assembled with the original parts. Magazine well is beveled. This is one sweet pistol and rare. Frank Pachmayr was one of the first custom gunsmiths for the 1911, he started a business in California and accurized many 1911 pistols, this is one of them and you do not see them every day. This is clearly a Pachmayr Custom. No box, no paperwork. What you see, is what you get. I have added a pair of the Pachmayr American Legend grips because I feel they look better than the plain jane wood grips from Colt. If you are looking for a rare, one of a kind, this is for you.  All local , state and federal laws apply. I would prefer a face to face transaction, but can ship, at buyers expense to an FFL. The price is $4,000. I am in Columbia,Tennessee.

title: For Sale:  BMG 5.56 Raptor Billet AR stripped lower
postcontent:
This is a pretty Rare Billet stripped AR lower made in Bend, OR

 From Manufacturer: New RAPTOR Custom AR Lower Receiver stripped and comes as pictured. The BMG Difference 99% of all AR15 Rifles manufactured have lower receivers made from forgings. Forgings are created by pouring molten aluminum alloy into a form, then compressing it at high pressure. The problem with utilizing forgings is that once the alloy cools, no two end up equal in specificity. Without equal specificity, it is impossible to make any jig to hold these forgings in place equally in order to allow the computerized milling machine to complete the job. All our lower receivers here at BMG are made from 6061 T651 aircraft grade alloy. Unlike other manufacturers that offer a similar product made individually from "Billet", (a solid block of aircraft grade aluminum alloy) our receivers are all made from bar stock, (Billet) four at a time and are not separated from each other until all milling is complete. By creating multiple receivers from the same piece of bar stock, we are able to maintain the closest tolerances available in the U.S. Today

The MWG 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16

High Capacity Magazine

The MWG 90 Rounder high capacity magazine for the AR-15/M16 provides you with the finest in state-of-the-art high capacity magazine design. The 90 Rounder's innovative snail-drum design and advanced space-age materials are combined to create a very light, completely reliable, low maintenance, high capacity magazine that will withstand a level of heavy field use that would destroy a metal magazine, while weighing 33% less.

The 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16 is designed for 5.56mm NATO or .223 Remington ammunition.

The 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16 is designed to be close to maintenance free. Never remove the silver-gray Teflon lubricant powder. Never Use any oil-based lubricant. Never disassemble MWG products, and never disassemble the 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16 .

The 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16 contains small parts & springs that may cause injury if improperly released. If repairs are required, return the magazine to MWG Company for repair. Any disassembly, alteration, re-adjustment, improper installation, or misuse of any MWG product voids all warranties.

Never attempt to load the 90 Rounder into the weapon or detach the 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16 from the weapon, with a cartridge in the chamber. Always lock the bolt back first and visually ensure the chamber is empty.

Because of its unique design, the 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16 can be left partially loaded for an extended period of time, but never store the 90 Rounder with more than 80 rounds loaded. Leaving the 90 Rounder for the stored with more than 80 rounds loaded may damage the springs and cause the weapon to malfunction. Never attempt to load more than 90 rounds. Loading more than 90 rounds may damage the magazine.

Always avoid lethal situations whenever possible. High capacity magazines such as the 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16 are intended to eliminate re-loading downtime for persons in unavoidable potentially lethal situations, but no product can fully protect the user from injury or death in a firefight. The knowing use of MWG products, when a potentially lethal situation could be avoided, will constitute an assumption of the known risks of engaging in a lethal situation.

LOADING 
The 90 Rounder for the AR-15/M16 must generate energy to reliably feed ammunition into the receiver at a consistent rate. As the magazine grows full, more energy must be exerted to load additional rounds. This energy is stored in a special spring & released to move the entire ammunition load during firing. It takes a lot of energy to reliably move 90 rounds of ammunition, and so it takes a lot of energy to load those same rounds. As the magazine nears capacity, the final rounds may require substantial energy to load.

title: For Sale:  Colt Medium Frame Lightning Rifle 44-40
postcontent: Colt Medium Frame Slide Action Lightning Rifle, Round Barrel, ca. 1894, 44 CLMR (44-40) Caliber, Serial #72xxx. Frame retains 95% bright original bright blue with a few light scratches and slight browning. Barrel and magazine tube retain 90% original bright blue with slight browning near frame. The hammer retains 50% original case colors and the crescent buttplate has faded. The bore is mint and crisp indicative of a rifle with this condition. Most screws appear untouched, but 2 have slight burring. Nice original walnut stock and checkered forearm have never been sanded and retain virtually all the original finish and checkering is sharp. There are no cracks or chips in the wood and the wood-to-metal fit is perfect with a few dings. All edges, English proofs and role stamping are crisp and sharp. Action is really tight like it has not been worked in a really long time. Notice the old oil and dirt residue or crud around the hammer, sights and other crevices that collectors like to see proving aged “untampered with” condition. The stock has a period cartouche in the right side of the stock stamped with the English seal and the words “Niger Coast Protectorate – Fire Arms Protection” around it. There is also another number stamped in the underside of the stock near the lower tang. This rifle has some nice history and the little bit that I found was that this rifle was ordered by England’s Parliament during a period that they denied accusations that England was participating or interfering with the Ivory Coast trade in Niger. It wasn’t until around turn of century that they publically announced they would send troops to help. However, this rifle proves that they were involved earlier. I have owned this rifle for 20 years and I have not seen another with this cartouche or history. This is a fine condition rifle that will make a fine addition to any Colt collection.  I give a 3 day inspection. title: For Sale:  Steyr M9-A1 9mm Pistol
postcontent:
Up for sale is my Steyr M9-A1, which is in virtually perfect condition. This pistol was completely checked out and test fired by Steyr Arms recently, and is functioning perfectly.  Included are two 17 rd. magazines, the original carrying case, two trigger keys, and owner's manual.  Additional pictures are available on request.

For those not familiar with the M9-A1, here are some facts and some comparisons with the "Other Austrian Pistol", the Glock 19:

The Steyr has a similar grip angle, but a smaller diameter and much more ergomonic grip shape.

The Steyr has a 4mm lower bore axis, for less muzzle flip and less perceived recoil.

The Steyr has a steel subframe incorporating the frame rails and the trigger / sear mechanism (very solid and precise).  This steel frame fits into the polymer grip as a module.  The glock uses its polymer grip as a frame to locate & hold the trigger mechanism, and the frame rails are molded into the polymer grip.

The Steyr uses unique fast acquisition trapezoidal / triangle combat sights which are made of steel and dove-tailed into the slide for easy replacement.  The glock uses plastic sights and front sight is staked in.

The Steyr has a shorter trigger pull, with a quicker reset.

The Steyr has a two round greater magazine capacity (17 rds versus 15).

The Steyr has a built-in keyed trigger lock as an additional safety feature.

The Steyr was initially designed for the .40 S&W, and then adapted for the less powerful 9mm.



My price is $475, face to face in N. Austin.  I'm not desperate to sell, so please don't make lowball offers (they will be ignored).  Trades for one or more firearms, +/- cash  may be possible (mostly "tactical" weapons or target guns), but I'm not very interested in hunting rifles or hunting shotguns, antiques, etc.  No archery equipment, computers, jet skis, etc.  Serious buyers will provide me with a (local) phone number if they want to talk in person. You want to flag all the listings, price gouging here on Armslist, I agree. Not saying its right go anywhere and everyone is raising their prices on everything. And honestly I would rather do something with the people who contact you on a listing you have and they lowball you so much, you come back w a counter offer they even low ball you even more and then all of sudden your listing has been removed by flagging, G, I wonder who just flagged my listing....?

If someone is asking $1500 for their AR type platform I bet they are more and willing to come down on the prices. But I know when you have someone asking $3000+ for a DPMS, MP, Bushmaster, Delton, PSA etc and they say firm now that's different.

No one is forcing you to purchase that $2500 AR.... Move on to the next listing and all this hipe will die down and everything will be back to normal, but the lowballers will still be out there.
